<p><b>Karl Pearson</b> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society" title="Fellow of the Royal Society" class="mw-redirect">FRS</a><sup id="cite_ref-frs_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-frs-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> (<span class="nowrap"><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ˈ</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'p' in 'pie'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">p</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ɪər/ 'ear' in 'beard'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ɪər</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'s' in 'sigh'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">s</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ɨ/ 'e' in 'roses'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ɨ</span></a></span><span class="IPA nopopups"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'n' in 'nigh'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">n</span></a></span><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span></span>) (27 March 1857 – 27 April 1936<sup id="cite_ref-rscat_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rscat-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>) (originally named <b>Carl</b>) was an influential <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/England" title="England">English</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician" title="Mathematician">mathematician</a> who has been credited with establishing the discipline of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_statistics" title="Mathematical statistics">mathematical statistics</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-year150_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-year150-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In 1911 he founded the world's first university statistics department at <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_College_London" title="University College London">University College London</a>. He was a proponent of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugenics" title="Eugenics">eugenics</a>, and a protégé and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biographer" title="Biographer" class="mw-redirect">biographer</a> of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Galton" title="Francis Galton">Sir Francis Galton</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sesquicentenary#Latin-derived_numerical_names" title="Sesquicentenary" class="mw-redirect">sesquicentenary</a> conference was held in London on 23 March 2007, to celebrate the 150th anniversary of his birth.<sup id="cite_ref-year150_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-year150-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
